arcelona, Catalunya, Spanje"},"en":{"0975–about 1060":"0975–about 1060","0975–1060":"0975–1060","0900–1074":"0900–1074","1011–1079":"1011–1079","0955–1005":"0955–1005","0955–0995":"0955–0995","0975":"0975","about 1060":"about 1060","1005":"1005","0995":"0995","1079":"1079","1011":"1011","1074":"1074","after 0995":"after 0995","1060":"1060","0955":"0955","0900":"0900","Lluçà, Barcelona, Cataluña, España":"Lluçà, Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain","l'Urgell, Lleida, Catalonia, Spain":"l'Urgell, Lleida, Catalonia, Spain","Europa":"Europe","Lluçà, Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain":"Lluçà, Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Llucá","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Adolfo, Antonio, Carmine, Gasper, Giacomo, Mario, Rosario, Sal, Aldo, Antonino, Domenic, Domenico, Dominico, Guido.","Italian and Romanian: from the personal name <i>Luca</i>, from Latin   Lucas  . Compare   Louque  .","Italian (southern; <b>Lucà</b>): possibly from a short form of Greek <i>Loukanos</i>, denoting an inhabitant of Lucania (see   Lucas  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Lucarelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Dino, Domenic, Franco, Olindo, Rocci, Rocco, Aldo, Carlo, Caterina, Chiara, Domenico.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a derivative of   Luca  ."]},{"name":"Luchini","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Oriano, Reno, Aldo, Angelo, Delio, Guido, Livio, Ottavio, Primo, Remo, Romano.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a derivative of   Luca  ."]},{"name":"Lucas","meanings":["English, German, French, Spanish, Portuguese, and Dutch: from the Latin personal name <i>Lucas</i> (Greek <i>Loukas</i>) ‘man from Lucania’. Lucania is a region of southern Italy thought to have been named in ancient times with a word meaning ‘bright’ or ‘shining’ (compare   Lucio  ). The Christian name owed its enormous popularity throughout Europe in the Middle Ages to Saint Luke the Evangelist, hence the development of this surname and many vernacular derivatives in most of the languages of Europe. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Greek   Loukas  , Hungarian <b>Lukács</b> (see   Lukacs  ), German, Dutch, etc.   Lukas  , Polish <b>Łukasz</b>, Czech and Slovak <b>Lukáš</b>, Czech <b>Lukeš</b>, Slovenian and Croatian <b>Lukež</b> (see   Lukes  ). Compare   Luke  .","Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Lùcais</b> (see   McLucas  ).","History: Jacques Lucas <i>dit</i> Lépine from Port-en-Bessin-Huppain in Calvados, France, married Françoise Capel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1653."]},{"name":"Luchetti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Everardo, Dante, Gino, Italo, Marco, Mario, Olindo, Ottavio, Rocco, Umberto.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a pet form of   Luca  ."]},{"name":"Louque","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Italian   Luca   ‘Lucas’."]},{"name":"Lucca","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Salvatore, Aldo, Angelo, Carlo, Dino, Domenic, Franco, Geno, Giuseppe, Livio, Marco.  Spanish Luis, Ana, Jose, Juan, Julio, Manuel, Orfilia.","Italian:","habitational name from Lucca in Tuscany or from Lucca Sicula in Agrigento province, Sicily, which was called simply Lucca until 1863. It was probably originally named with a Celtic element meaning ‘marshy’."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sunifredo II de Llucá was born in 0975, in Lluçà, Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain, his father, Guisade de Lluçà, was 20 and his mother, Oda de Besora, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Ermesenda de Balsareny. He died about 1060, in l'Urgell, Lleida, Catalonia, Spain, at the age of 86."},"et":{"0975–about 1060":"0975–umbes 1060","0975–1060":"0975–1060","0900–1